This means that a generic PAC-Bayes bound applied to mixtures of experts will depend on the sum of the KL divergences corresponding to the gating functions and each of the experts. Obviously, this sum could be very large. By imposing \(\)-LDP to the gating functions as in our approach, we can eliminate the stochasticity associated to the gating functions, and rid our bounds of the (potentially very large) \((Q_{}\,\|\,P_{})\) term. Instead, it is \(\)-LDP which controls our gating functions to ensure generalization. Furthermore, our bounds replace the sum of the KL divergences of the experts by a \((x^{})\)-weighted average, which means we can have many more experts with almost no penalty from the theoretical point of view. Indeed, our bounds only depend on the number \(n\) of experts logarithmically, through the use of the union bound.

